  "opinion": "As a 23-year-old woman working as a cleaner in Rome, I’ve observed how the gender gap in science often feels like a distant, almost abstract issue—until you see it in the people you interact with daily. My parents’ limited education shaped my early curiosity about the world, but growing up in a small Italian town, I never had access to the same resources as my peers who attended better-funded schools. Now, as someone with an upper secondary education, I’ve noticed that science fields often seem to exclude women not just in terms of numbers, but in the very language and expectations around them. For instance, when I talk to students who want to pursue STEM careers, they’re often told, 'You’re not cut out for this'—a comment that echoes the same biases I’ve seen in classrooms and workplaces. The gap isn’t just about fewer women in labs or engineering departments; it’s about the subtle messages that tell girls they’re not 'the right type' for science. Should we address it? Absolutely. But how? By creating spaces where girls feel seen and supported from the start—not through grand gestures, but through small, consistent actions. In my community, I’ve started helping younger girls with science projects in my garden, showing them how plants and nature follow scientific principles. It’s not about fixing the system overnight; it’s about building confidence through relatable examples. The most important thing is to stop treating science as something only for boys and start framing it as a journey of discovery, one that anyone can enjoy. After all, the best science isn’t about who’s in the lab—it’s about who’s curious enough to ask questions.",
